cool = classroom object oriented language
* A complete compiler
- Cool -> MIPS assembly language
* In 5 programing assignments:
- Write a Cool program
- Lexical analysis
- Parsing
- Semantic analysis
- Code generation
All 4 phases are plug compatible
Suggestions for optimizations will be given as optional.
COOL programs end in extension .cl

Structure of a cool program:
class Main {
    main():Int { 1 };
}; // notice that it ends in semicolon

cool is an expression language.
We need to put the return type of the function, so in this case we placed Int

Installing spim:
yay -S spim-svn
Do you need sudo?
No, do not type sudo yay.
yay handles it automatically: Run the command as a normal user.
Security risk: yay explicitly blocks you from running it with sudo because building packages from the AUR as root is dangerous.
Elevated prompt: yay will automatically prompt you for your sudo password at the very end of the process when it is ready to install the built package.
File Locations
Once installed, the package places files in these standard system directories:
Binary Executable: /usr/bin/spim
Architecture Files: /usr/lib/spim/ (contains the standard trap handler)
Documentation: /usr/share/doc/spim/
Man Pages: /usr/share/man/man1/spim.1.gzYou can verify the exact installation path on your system by running which spim.
